title: For Sale:  Samozaryadnaya Vintovka Tokare -- RUSSIAN SVT-40 1941 7.62X54R SEMI AUTO RIFLE SVT40
postcontent: Very rare hard to find (1941) RUSSIAN SVT-40 RIFLE - 7.62x54r caliber semi-automatic rifle. 10 round detachable magazine. The Samozaryadnaya Vintovka Tokareva (SVT-40) was designed by Soviet Arms Designer Fedor Tokarev. It was manufactured between 1941 and 1945. The SVT-40 is an improved and simplified rifle design over the SVT-38. During WWII SVT-40 rifles were highly prized captures by both German and Finnish troops. Many pictures in books of German troops on the eastern front carrying the SVT-40. The biggest issue with the SVT 40 is the ejection of the spent casing due to improper gas cartridge adjustment and improper powder loads. DO NOT use any loads over 150 grain as this will destroy the gas chamber. Overall condition is rated as fair to good for an old surplus military rifle that will never be imported again into the USA. 10 magazine is an aftermarket, so not all original, all other numbers match THAT I CAN TELL. Wood stock has 3 cracks/splits at rear top of receiver and at bottom of mag well. Gun has some surface rust spots. I would grade gun and bore as fair to good condition.

As the NY SAFE act currently stands, there are NO private OR FFL sales of any firearms matching the criteria of "assault" weapons within the borders of NY.  There are a lot of weapons listed, for instance the DPMS carbine listed on Saturday the 16th that comes with a drum mag, 5 PMAGs, a bayonet and lug, and telescoping stock.  I have offered to purchase this weapon as out out-of-state buyer where the weapon and accessories will be transferred in PA where they are legal, and will remain after sale.  So far I have had no response, which leads me to believe that the buyer is either too lazy to drive to an FFL in PA to conduct the sale, or too lazy to have the buyer (me) pay shipping for an FFL in NY to transfer the weapon and all accessories to an FFL in PA where I can then pick it up.  One would think an offer to buy would solicit a response.

... or the seller is an investigator trying to collar a few people with a felony for the crime of exercising one's right to arms and right to property.  This "seller" wants the transaction to take place in NY most likely so his buddies dressed up as mall ninjas can give the prospective buyer a free pair of silver bracelets.

Stay vigilant, gentlemen.  While many police are honorable people who will exercise good judgement in the course of their duties, there are liberal district attorneys and other officers in the state police who will take the stance that "the law is the law," and will actively try to ruin someone's life who is only trying to acquire an AR or AK before the registration period ends in 2014 because they were not afforded the ability to buy one with Cuomo's blitzkrieg legislative tactic.  They will actively try to enforce the largely unenforceable ban on private sales by conducting sting operations with plenty of press coverage to keep others from selling their property to others before the registration period closes.

It's quite simple, conduct your private sales out of state... all it takes is a little extra time and gas money.  I would be extremely leery of sellers who are unwilling to ship to an FFL out of state, or are unwilling to conduct the transaction out of state, especially when the accessories are not legal in NYS.

The Special Operations Forces Combat Assault Rifle (SCAR)[9] is a modular rifle made by FN Herstal (FNH) for the United States Special Operations Command (SOCOM) to satisfy the requirements of the SCAR competition.[10] This family of rifles consist of two main types. The SCAR-L, for "light", is chambered in the 5.56×45mm NATO cartridge and the SCAR-H, for "heavy", fires 7.62×51mm NATO. Both are available in Long Barrel and Close Quarters Combat variants.

The FN SCAR systems completed low rate initial production testing in June 2007.[11] After some delays, the first rifles began being issued to operational units in April 2009, and a battalion of the US 75th Ranger Regiment was the first large unit deployed into combat with 600 of the rifles in 2009.[12] The US Special Operations Command has currently cancelled their purchase of the Mk 16 SCAR-L and are planning to remove the rifle from their inventory by 2013. However, they plan to purchase 5.56 mm conversion kits for the Mk 17, supplanting the loss of the Mk 16.[13] The SCAR is now one of the competing weapons in the Individual Carbine competition which aims to find a replacement for the M4 Carbine.[14]
